Follow four simple rules, and
the solid wood paneling In your
home will remain in perfect con-
dition without maintenance for 20
years or longer.


Earl Cox, president Of the Ari-
IONA Wood Council. reports state
lumbermen are now offering such
information to home owners as
part of their normal customer
service. Proper selection and
application Of paneling not only
beautified rooms, but also makes
a trouble-free permanent install
lation.


The four rules, Cox says, are
these:


|. Have the dealer help you
choose a species with natural
wear resistance and nail-holding
power.


2. Make certain paneling Is
properly easoned. All grades of
Arizona-grown pine have strict
limits on moisture content, so
that the wood cannot shrink or
swell.


8. When the paneling Is de-
livered, stack 1t on narrow sep
arator sticks with all sides ex-
posed, preferably In the room
where it Is to be used. This will
condition 1t to the prevailing
humidity.


4. Treat backs and ends with
a penetrating sealer or other
moismre-resistant coating. This
will protect 1t against such house.
hold activities as cooking and
laundering, which generate heat
and humidity.

Fora Foley, heavyweight
fighter of Chandler, Ariz.. is now
ranked No. 8 by Ring Magazine
and No. S by the World Boxing
Association. Foley was ranked
No. for two years while Floyd
Patterson was champion but
never got chance to fight him.


The Arizonan has been In the
first ten rankings since 1856 and
he has never had an offer ofight
for the crown.


1t is rumored that promoters
are trying to arrange a match
for him and Patterson in San
Francisco's Cow Palace in Sep
TENDER.


Fora has been boxing pro-
fessionally since 1853. His
record is 90 wins, E draws and 2
losses. This year he had had
five fights. winning four and
drawing one.

NEW YORK Roy wilkins,
executive secretary Of the Ma
tional Association for the Ad-
vancement of Colored People,
released the text of telegram
which he sent to the five other
jor civil rights leaders on July
u. proposing a meeting to dis
cuss how to oppose the election
of Sen. G oldwater.


The wire sent to the Rev. Mar
tin Luther King, Jr., president
of the Southern Chris dan Leader
ship Conference; James L. Far
mer, national director Of the
Congress of Racial Equality;
Whitney Nj. Young, Jr., executive
director of the National Urban
League; A. Philip Randolph.
chairman of the Negro American
Labor Council: and John Lewis,
chairman of the Student Non
violent Coordinating Committee,
reads:


Nothing could be palmer than
that each battle won imposes
new challenges until final VIC
tory is achieved. The events
of the past u hours, including
the tragic violence in Harlem
and the end of the Wallace
candidacy for president. hard
on the heels of the G oldwater
nomination, are all linked to-
gether In ways that may pro-
duce the sternest challenge we
have yet seen. The promise
of the Civil Rights Act Of
1864 could we'll be diminished
or nullified and a decade of
increasingly violent and futile
disorder ushered in If we do
not play our hand coolly and
intelligently. There is no
safety in assumptions that
Goldwater cannot win the cleo
ton. He can win it and he
can be helped to win it If
enough wrong moves are made.
1t is of highest importance we
take counsel at earliest
moment to ensure that with
out modifying any essential
position we do nothing to pro-
duce votes for G oldwater. None
of us will knowingly jeopardize
the prospects we have gainedby
such massive sacrifices and we
can best ensure against such
dangers by close and precise
agreement among our
organizations.


The leaders responded and on
July % a cease order for further
demonstrations was issued.

After studying "do's" and
"dont's" of safe driving, safety
experts of Sentry Insurance an
nounce the 10 most important
precautions for motorists. Sur
veys show vast majority of
drivers think of themselves as
"better than average drivers"
Yet, most traffic accidents are a
result of violation of the law or
common-sense rule of safe driv-
ing.


Slow down and enjoy your trip.
"Speed too fast" is number one
killer. Adjust speed to road con-
ditions. In heavy rain, front
wheels actually leave road at 80
m.p.h. and skim on rain film.
Stay on your side. Allow plenty
of time and distance for passing.
Don't pass on an intersection,
curve, bridge, railroad tracks.
Yield right of way. An intersec-
ton is a danger zone, proceed
with caution.


If you're driving, don't drink.
Two drinks can blunt refexes.
Avoid driving under influence of
drugs. Effects Of "pep pills."
tranquilizers, other medicines,
can be dangerous behind the
wheel. Ask your doctor about eff
fects of remedies prescribed.
Keep your distance. Allow at least
one car length between you and
car ahead for each 10 m.p.h.
Make exit gracefully. Get in right
lane early when leaving super
highway. Turn into "speed
change" exit lane without slack
ening speed, then accelerate
rapidly.


Use directional signals. Failure
to do so may bring a traffic ticket.
Obey traffic signals. Passing of
STOP signs is a common acct
dent cause according to Sentry
Insurance findings.


Finally, check up before starting
up. Lights, signals, brakes, tires,
steering, exhaust system, wipers,
horn and rear-view mirrors
should be in top condition.
